Predict bike rental to reduce costs and improve customer satisfaction

using Decision Tree, Random Forest and Neural Network

ML2 Project with Robert Wojciechowski

Link to dataset: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/bike+sharing+dataset

Dataset structure:

  • instant: Unique ID for each row.
  • dteday: Date (in format YYYY-MM-DD)
  • season: Season (1:winter, 2:spring, 3:summer, 4:fall)
  • yr: Year (0: 2011, 1:2012)
  • mnth: Month (1 to 12)
  • holiday: If it's holiday (extracted from https://dchr.dc.gov/page/holiday-schedules)
  • weekday: Which day of the week (integer)
  • workingday: If day is neither weekend nor holiday is 1, otherwise is 0 (not all holiday are bank holiday)
  • weathersit:
    • 1: Clear, Few clouds, Partly cloudy, Partly cloudy
    • 2: Mist + Cloudy, Mist + Broken clouds, Mist + Few clouds, Mist
    • 3: Light Snow, Light Rain + Thunderstorm + Scattered clouds, Light Rain + Scattered clouds
    • 4: Heavy Rain + Ice Pallets + Thunderstorm + Mist, Snow + Fog
  • temp : Normalized temperature in Celsius. The values are derived via (t-t_min)/(t_max-t_min), t_min=-8, t_max=+39 (only in hourly scale)
  • atemp: Normalized feeling temperature in Celsius. The values are derived via (t-t_min)/(t_max-t_min), t_min=-16, t_max=+50 (only in hourly scale)
  • hum: Normalized humidity. The values are divided to 100 (max)
  • windspeed: Normalized wind speed. The values are divided to 67 (max)
  • casual: count of casual users
  • registered: count of registered users
  • cnt: count of total rental bikes including both casual and registered

About the model

Can I create a model that, for a given set of characteristics (weather conditions, holiday or not, season, day of the week, etc.), can accurately predict how many bikes will be rented?

Generally bike rental services have some significant costs related to the insurance, and this of course depends on how many people will rent a bike because:

More clients rent public bikes → Higher chance of a damaged bike → Higer costs of insurance

But the problem is not only about the costs, because by predicting the bike usage the company can improve their client satisfaction.

How?

If the company knows that in few days there's a high chance of a huge bike rentals, they can deliver a targeted maintainance service and there will be much less chance that a client finds a damaged bike.

Removing outliers¶

To fill outliers I first remove them and then i fill with the mean of the explanatory variable.

In [18]:
wind_humidity=pd.DataFrame(df,columns=['windspeed','humidity'])
cnames=['windspeed','humidity']

for i in cnames:
    q75, q25 = np.percentile(wind_humidity.loc[:,i],[75,25])
    iqr=q75-q25
    min=q25-(iqr*1.5)
    max=q75+(iqr*1.5)
    wind_humidity.loc[wind_humidity.loc[:,i]<min,:i]=np.nan  #Replace with NA
    wind_humidity.loc[wind_humidity.loc[:,i]>max,:i]=np.nan  #Replace with NA

#Imputating the outliers by mean Imputation
wind_humidity['windspeed']=wind_humidity['windspeed'].fillna(wind_humidity['windspeed'].mean())
wind_humidity['humidity']=wind_humidity['humidity'].fillna(wind_humidity['humidity'].mean())
In [19]:
df['windspeed']=df['windspeed'].replace(wind_humidity['windspeed'])
df['humidity']=df['humidity'].replace(wind_humidity['humidity'])

In [21]:
#Create the correlation matrix
matrix=df[["temp","atemp","humidity","windspeed","casual","registered","total_count"]].corr()
mask=np.array(matrix)
mask[np.tril_indices_from(mask)]=False
fig,ax=plt.subplots(figsize=(15,8))
sns.heatmap(matrix,mask=mask,vmax=0.8,square=True,annot=True,ax=ax)
ax.set_title('Correlation matrix')
plt.show()

We can observed that some features are positively correlated or some are negatively correlated to each other. The temp and atemp are highly positively correlated to each other, it means that both are carrying same information so that's why i don't consider atemp as a training feature.

The total_count, casual and registered are highly positively correlated to each other and not relevant for the training of the model.
